","1480–1513":"1480–1513","1488–Male":"1488–Deceased","1509–1557":"1509–1557","1455–Male":"1455–Deceased","1460–Female":"1460–Deceased","1557":"1557","1513":"1513","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1487":"1487","1530":"1530","1494":"1494","1509":"1509","1460":"1460","1508":"1508","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","Carleton, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carleton, Ayrshire, Scotland","Wales":"Wales","Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Carleton, Ayr, Scotland, Great Britain":"Carleton, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Jacques, Adelard, Antoine, Julien, Pierre, Alain, Camille, Cecile, Emile, Fernand.","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Marie  .","English: from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Marion</i>, usually a pet form of   Mary  , but in medieval England sometimes also used for <i>Margery</i>. Compare   Marriott  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Marie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Cecile, Alain, Benoit, Camille, Edouard, Francoise, Jean Jacques, Jean-Philippe, Stephane.","French and English (Jersey; also Surrey and Middlesex): from the female personal name <i>Marie</i>, Latin   Maria  . In England it is in part of Huguenot origin. Compare   Mary  .","French (<b>Marié</b>): from <i>marié</i> ‘married’, the past participle of <i>marier</i> ‘to marry’, a nickname for a man newly married or perhaps for a son-in-law, or a status name for a married individual used to distinguish him from an unmarried namesake. Compare   Lemarie   and   Marier  ."]},{"name":"Marean","meanings":["Scottish: probably a variant of   Marion  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Marion was born in 1487, in Cathcart, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Alan Cathcart Master of Cathcart, was 33 and her mother, Margaret Chalmers, was 28. She married Robert Cathcart in 1508, in Carleton, Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"1487–":"1487–Surnud","1487–Female":"1487–Surnud","1490–1530":"1490–1530","1494–Female":"1494–Surnud","1480–1513":"1480–1513","1488–Male":"1488–Surnud","1509–1557":"1509–1557","1455–Male":"1455–Surnud","1460–Female":"1460–Surnud","1557":"1557","1513":"1513","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1487":"1487","1530":"1530","1494":"1494","1509":"1509","1460":"1460","1508":"1508","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","Carleton, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Carleton, Ayrshire, Scotland","Wales":"Wales","Cathcart, Renfrewshire